# ACL (Application Configuration Layer) Configuration

menuconfig ACL
	bool "ACL (Application Configuration Layer)"
	default n
	select OSAL
	help
	  Application Configuration Layer provides business logic to hardware
	  device mapping and high-level application APIs.

	  ACL is the top layer of the ES-Middleware SDK stack, providing:
	  - Business function abstraction (telemetry, commands, data storage)
	  - Device-to-function mapping (which sensor provides which telemetry)
	  - Application-level APIs (hide hardware complexity)
	  - Configuration management (device tables, parameter sets)

	  Architecture:
	  Applications use ACL APIs to access business functions without
	  knowing the underlying hardware details. ACL translates business
	  requests into PDL peripheral operations.

	  Example:
	  - Application: "Get temperature from thermal sensor #3"
	  - ACL: Maps sensor #3 to satellite module 0x05, channel 2
	  - PDL: Reads data from satellite via CAN bus
	  - HAL: Performs low-level CAN communication

	  Memory footprint: ~20KB code + configuration tables

	  Use cases:
	  - Complex systems with many devices
	  - Applications that need hardware abstraction
	  - Systems with configurable device mappings

	  Dependencies: OSAL

	  Note: ACL provides configuration management only. Runtime data
	  caching (telemetry cache) is provided by the separate TM_CACHE module.

	  Recommended: Enable for application-level development

	  If unsure, say Y.

if ACL

menu "ACL Build Configuration"

config ACONFIG_BUILD_STATIC
	bool "Build static library (.a)"
	default n
	help
	  Build ACL as a static library (libacl.a).

	  Static linking advantages:
	  - No runtime dependencies
	  - Configuration tables embedded in executable
	  - Slightly faster

	  Recommended: Enable for embedded systems with fixed configurations

config ACONFIG_BUILD_SHARED
	bool "Build shared library (.so)"
	default n
	help
	  Build ACL as a shared library (libacl.so).

	  Shared library advantages:
	  - Can update device mappings without recompiling apps
	  - Smaller executable size
	  - Code sharing between processes

	  Use cases:
	  - Systems with multiple applications using ACL
	  - Field-updatable device configurations

	  Recommended: Enable for multi-application systems

endmenu

menu "ACL Configuration"

config ACONFIG_MAX_DEVICES
	int "Maximum number of devices"
	default 64
	range 1 256
	help
	  Maximum number of devices that can be configured in ACL.

	  This limits the size of the device configuration table.
	  Each device entry contains mapping information (device ID,
	  peripheral type, channel, parameters, etc.).

	  Memory impact: ~64 bytes per device slot
	  Total memory: ACONFIG_MAX_DEVICES × 64 bytes

	  Recommended values:
	  - RTOS Minimal: 8-16 devices (~1KB)
	  - Linux Minimal: 32 devices (~2KB)
	  - Linux Standard: 64 devices (~4KB)
	  - Linux Full: 128-256 devices (~8-16KB)

	  Examples:
	  - Simple sensor node: 8-16 devices
	  - Satellite payload: 32-64 devices
	  - Complex industrial system: 128-256 devices

	  Note: Set this to the maximum number of physical devices
	  (sensors, actuators, etc.) your system will manage.

endmenu

endif # ACL
